## Thread.Abort Migration to .NET 8

### Why This Breaks

`Thread.Abort()` throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` in .NET 6+. `ThreadAbortException` is never thrown, and `Thread.ResetAbort()` is obsolete (`SYSLIB0006`). The entire forced-termination model is gone — you must use **cooperative cancellation**.

### Pattern Analysis

| Location | Pattern | Replacement |
|----------|---------|-------------|
| `Stop()` → `_workerThread.Abort()` | Cancellable work loop | `CancellationTokenSource.Cancel()` |
| `catch (ThreadAbortException)` | Control flow cleanup | `catch (OperationCanceledException)` |
| `Thread.ResetAbort()` | Continue after abort | `token.IsCancellationRequested` check |
| `GetNextItem()` (may block) | Blocking call interruption | Pass `CancellationToken` to unblock |
| `Thread.Sleep(2000)` | Graceful wait | `Thread.Join(timeout)` |

### Migrated Code

```csharp
public class BackgroundProcessor : IDisposable
{
    private Thread? _workerThread;
    private CancellationTokenSource? _cts;

    public void Start()
    {
        _cts = new CancellationTokenSource();
        var token = _cts.Token;
        _workerThread = new Thread(() => ProcessLoop(token))
        {
            IsBackground = true
        };
        _workerThread.Start();
    }

    private void ProcessLoop(CancellationToken token)
    {
        while (!token.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            try
            {
                var item = GetNextItem(token); // pass token to unblock
                ProcessItem(item);
            }
            catch (OperationCanceledException) when (token.IsCancellationRequested)
            {
                // Clean up partial work — same logic that was in
                // the ThreadAbortException catch block
                RollbackCurrentTransaction();
                // No ResetAbort needed — we control the loop condition.
                // Loop will exit naturally on next iteration check.
            }
            finally
            {
                FlushBuffers();
            }
        }
    }

    public void Stop()
    {
        if (_cts is null) return;

        _cts.Cancel();  // signal cooperative cancellation

        // Give the thread time to finish gracefully
        if (_workerThread?.IsAlive == true)
            _workerThread.Join(TimeSpan.FromSeconds(2));

        // If still alive after timeout, it's a bug — the thread must
        // cooperate. Thread.Abort is NOT available as a fallback.
    }

    public void Dispose()
    {
        Stop();
        _cts?.Dispose();
        _cts = null;
    }
}
```

### What Must Change in `GetNextItem`

This is the **critical pitfall**. If `GetNextItem()` blocks (e.g., on a queue, socket, or `WaitHandle`), the cancellation token won't interrupt it unless you wire it in:

```csharp
// BEFORE — blocks forever, only Thread.Abort could break it
private Item GetNextItem()
{
    return _queue.Take(); // BlockingCollection<T>.Take()
}

// AFTER — cancellation-aware
private Item GetNextItem(CancellationToken token)
{
    return _queue.Take(token); // throws OperationCanceledException
}
```

If the blocking call doesn't accept a token (e.g., raw `WaitHandle.WaitOne()`):

```csharp
// Replace WaitOne() with WaitAny + token
WaitHandle.WaitAny(new[] { myEvent, token.WaitHandle });
token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested();
```

### Key Pitfalls

| Pitfall | Details |
|---------|---------|
| **Blocking calls ignore tokens** | `Thread.Sleep`, `socket.Receive`, raw `WaitOne` don't check tokens. Replace with `token.WaitHandle.WaitOne(ms)`, async I/O, or overloads accepting `CancellationToken`. |
| **No force-kill fallback** | If the thread doesn't cooperate, `Stop()` can hang. Add checkpoint calls (`token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested()`) inside `ProcessItem` if it's long-running. |
| **Dispose `CancellationTokenSource`** | It's `IDisposable` — leaking it causes timer/callback leaks. Implement `IDisposable` on the processor. |
| **Don't swallow `OperationCanceledException`** | The `when (token.IsCancellationRequested)` filter ensures you only catch *your* cancellation, not someone else's. |
| **`ResetAbort` → loop continuation** | The old `ResetAbort` kept the thread alive. Now the loop condition (`!token.IsCancellationRequested`) handles this naturally — if you want to continue processing after a per-item cancellation, use a per-item `CancellationTokenSource` linked to a parent token. |
